<P>
Book Review; Page 9; Book Review Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
218 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
ROSE-COLORED RETROSPECTION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Reviewing Barbara Ehrenreich's new "Fear of Falling" (Book Review, Aug. 20), 
David Rieff states: "In the 1950s, as Ehrenreich demonstrates brilliantly, 
American writers, academics and politicians all came perilously close to 
agreeing with the college newspaper editor who remarked in 1957 that "All the 
problems are solved." Even Arthur Schlesinger Jr. asserted that the problems of 
poverty had been largely eliminated though there remained "enclaves where the 
underprivileged still can be found, as in the Southern Alleghenies or the rural 
Deep South.' " 
</P>
<P>
This is a joke. No matter how many fantasy pronouncements were made at the time 
-- or now in retrospect -- the fact is that this country faced an economic 
recession in the late '50s when unemployment climbed above the "dangerous" 6% 
mark . . and not just in the Alleghenies or the Deep South. Don't take my word 
for it; just check the records. 
</P>
<P>
Explanation for this schism is simple. Economists -- whether their names are 
Ehrenreich, Schlesinger, Greenspan or Volcker -- all inhabit a different 
planet, breathe different air, than do the rest of us. They're no more reliable 
today than were their predecessors 60 years ago who preached that "The business 
of America is business" and that prosperity was here to stay. 
</P>
<P>
DAVID R. MOSS 
</P>
<P>
LOS ANGELES 
</P>
</TEXT>
