<HEADLINE>
<P>
WAKE US WHEN YOU'RE READY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The best news we've heard in a long time is that sleep researchers now think a 
little shut-eye in the afternoon is precisely what nature intended for the 
refreshment of mankind. 
</P>
<P>
We ourselves have always been acutely aware of the biological urge to cork off 
as the day drags on, but that's something we thought it prudent not to talk 
about in polite society. The truth of the matter is that our inclination to 
catch a nap has always been accompanied by a feeling of profound moral 
irresponsibility, no doubt arising from the culturally imposed notion that 
after the age of 5, real people sleep only when it's dark outside. Now, thanks 
to the studies of scientists around the world, that terrible burden of guilt 
has been lifted. From here on we will feel at liberty to nod off any afternoon 
we feel like it, without regret, resistance, shame or remorse. 
</P>
<P>
Of course, any such naps will have to be enjoyed only on weekends and holidays, 
since our employer -- like others -- frowns on the prospect of paying people 
for snoozing on the job. As it happens, employers may be doing themselves a 
disservice by holding to this traditional attitude. It's long been known that 
work performance declines in mid-afternoon as loginess takes hold. Worse, the 
accident rate rises significantly in the afternoon hours, a fact that seems 
directly linked to a fall-off in mental alertness. 
</P>
<P>
Conventional wisdom has long held that afternoon sleepiness is the price we pay 
for eating heavy lunches. Not so, say researchers. What studies have determined 
is that drowsiness sets in, lunch or no lunch, about 12 hours after the 
midpoint of the day's main sleeping period. Thus if a person sleeps from 11 
p.m. to 6 a.m., chances are that by 3 or 3:30 in the afternoon the body is 
ready -- if not frantically in need of -- a nice restorative doze. 
</P>
<P>
People in tropical climates have always been smart enough to go with the flow 
instead of trying to fight what nature has programmed, making the siesta a 
normal and salutary part of their lives. Maybe it's time for people in other 
parts of the world to get back in touch with their biological imperative and 
set aside a portion of each afternoon for an efficiency-raising, 
grumpiness-reducing nap. That's a splendid idea for someone to drop into the 
boss's suggestion box. Don't forget to wake us if you get an answer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Editorial 
</P>
</TYPE>
