<HEADLINE>
<P>
980 ELEPHANT TUSKS SEIZED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Reuters 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WINDHOEK, Namibia 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Police said they made Africa's biggest seizure of illicit ivory Saturday in 
Namibia, arresting 22 suspected smugglers in the pre-dawn operation. About 980 
elephant tusks and 14 rhino horns weighing more than seven tons were seized in 
a series of raids, police spokesman Colonel Johan Meintjies said. 
</P>
<P>
"This is the biggest haul made in Africa and could be the biggest ever made," 
he said. 
</P>
<P>
Meintjies said the ivory had been transported Friday in a refrigerated 
vegetable truck from Rundu on the Angolan border to Okahandja, near Windhoek, 
before the police launched their raids. 
</P>
<P>
He said the nationalities of the 22, who included whites and blacks, were not 
yet known but six were Portuguese-speaking. 
</P>
</TEXT>
