<HEADLINE>
<P>
SOUTHERN CALIFORNIA JOB MARKET; 
</P>
<P>
PART THREE: EXTRAS THAT COUNT; 
</P>
<P>
IT MAY BE LESS FUN AT THE TOP 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MARTHA GROVES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Fun apparently can prove more elusive for managers than for those they 
supervise. Hewitt Associates, a benefits consulting firm based in Lincolnshire, 
Ill., found that 18% of rank-and-file workers at an accounting company viewed 
having fun as one of six important motivators on the job. And 83% of those 
employees said they were satisfied with the level of fun in their jobs. 
</P>
<P>
Among executives, 29% picked having fun as one of six important motivators, but 
only 72% of them were satisfied with the degree of fun in their work. MARTHA 
GROVES 
</P>
</TEXT>
